[Ace_XR.pdf - page 1] - Suppository 500 mg: Each suppository contains Paracetamol BP 500 mg. How this medicine works (pharmacology) Ace is a formulation of Paracetamol (Acetaminophen), which is one of the safest and most widely used analgesic and antipyretic agents. Paracetamol produces analgesia by elevating the pain threshold and antipyresis through action on the hypothalamic heat-regulating centre. At recommended doses, paracetamol has minimal effect on the cardiovascular and respiratory systems, and it does not cause gastric irritation or ulceration like many NSAIDs. Paracetamol is rapidly and almost completely absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract and is distributed into most body tissues. It is metabolised primarily in the liver and excreted in the urine mainly as glucuronide and sulphate conjugates. Only a small fraction is metabolised to a reactive intermediate which may cause liver damage in overdose.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 2] Following rectal administration, absorption may be slower than from the stomach. The plasma half-life is approximately 1.5 to 3.0 hours in subjects with normal hepatic function. Indications - Relief of pain and fever associated with common cold, influenza and other viral or bacterial infections. - Headache, including migraine. - Toothache and teething pain. - Muscular pain, myalgia, backache, sprains and strains. - Dysmenorrhoea. - Post-operative pain. - Pain of osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis as advised by a physician. - Pain and fever associated with vaccination. Dosage and administration The lowest effective dose should be used for the shortest duration necessary to relieve symptoms. Dose and frequency depend on age, body weight, dosage form and clinical response. Always follow the physicianâ€™s instructions and the information on the product label. - Adults and children over 12 years (tablet / XR tablet / oral liquid): Commonly 500â€“ 1000 mg every 4â€“6 hours as needed, without exceeding the maximum recommended daily dose printed on the pack. - Extended Release (Ace XR) tablets are designed for prolonged effect and should be swallowed whole with water; they must not be crushed, chewed or broken.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 2] - Children: Dosage is based on body weight, usually 10â€“15 mg/kg per dose every 4â€“6 hours, up to the maximum number of doses per 24 hours as indicated in the leaflet. - Paediatric drops / syrup / suspension: Dose should be carefully measured using the supplied dropper or measuring cup. Age- and weight-specific recommendations are provided in the original dosage table. - Suppositories: Used when the oral route is not feasible; dosing follows standard paediatric and adult suppository regimens as detailed in the leaflet. Note: The original Ace leaflet contains a detailed weight-based and age-based dosage table for paediatric preparations and suppositories, which should be consulted for exact dosing. Contraindications & warnings - Known sensitivity or hypersensitivity to paracetamol or any component of the formulation. - Severe hepatic impairment or active liver disease. - Concomitant use with other paracetamol-containing products should be avoided to prevent overdose.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 3] Precautions Use with caution in patients with impaired hepatic or renal function, chronic alcohol use, chronic malnutrition, dehydration or anaemia. Prolonged or frequent use at higher than recommended doses may increase the risk of liver damage. Patients should not take other paracetamol-containing medicines concurrently. If fever persists or pain does not improve within a few days, medical advice should be sought. Side effects Side effects are generally mild, though haematological reactions have been reported. Possible adverse reactions include: - Skin rashes and other allergic reactions, occasionally severe, including urticaria and angioedema. - Blood dyscrasias such as thrombocytopenia, leukopenia or neutropenia (rare). - Pancreatitis has been reported rarely, usually in association with liver dysfunction. Drug interactions Paracetamol may interact with other drugs, particularly those affecting hepatic enzymes. Enzyme-inducing drugs such as certain antiepileptics or rifampicin may increase formation of toxic metabolites and enhance risk of hepatotoxicity. Chronic alcohol use increases the risk of liver damage when combined with paracetamol. Use in pregnancy & lactation Paracetamol is commonly used during pregnancy and lactation and, when used at recommended doses, is generally considered safe.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 3] As with all medicines, paracetamol should be used during pregnancy or breast-feeding only on medical advice and for the shortest duration necessary. Overdose Paracetamol overdose is a serious medical emergency. Early symptoms within 24 hours may include pallor, nausea, vomiting, anorexia and abdominal pain. Liver damage may become apparent 12â€“48 hours after ingestion and may lead to hepatic failure, encephalopathy, coma and death.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 4] Management includes prompt gastric lavage when appropriate, measurement of plasma paracetamol concentration and administration of N-acetylcysteine according to established treatment guidelines, together with supportive and symptomatic care. Storage - Store below 30Â°C in a cool, dry place. - Protect from light and moisture. - Keep out of the reach of children. How supplied - Ace XR Extended Release Tablets: Supplied in blister packs (exact pack sizes as per marketed presentation). - Ace tablets, syrup, suspension, paediatric drops and suppositories: Supplied in various blister pack and bottle presentations as described on the individual packs. Usage Usage: fever, headache, migraine, toothache, body pain, muscular pain, post-vaccination fever, cold- and flu-related pain and fever.
